1 2. A petition for the issuance of a public transportation
2 trespass order filed pursuant to this section must include all of the
3 following information:
4 (a) Evidence of the conviction of the person against whom the
5 order is sought for a violation of NRS 200.471 or 200.481.
6 (b) A detailed statement of facts demonstrating that the order
7 is necessary to protect public safety and transit operations.
8 (c) The proposed duration and scope of the order, which must
9 not exceed 18 months.
10 3. Within 30 days after a petition for the issuance of a public
11 transportation trespass order is filed pursuant to this section, the
12 court shall hold a hearing to determine whether to issue the order.
13 The person against whom the order is sought is entitled to notice
14 of the hearing and an opportunity to be heard at the hearing.
15 4. The court may issue a public transportation trespass order
16 pursuant to this section if the court finds, by a preponderance of
17 the evidence, that:
18 (a) The person against whom the order is sought poses a
19 continuing threat to public safety or transit operations; and
20 (b) The order is necessary to protect public safety or to prevent
21 future disruptions to transit operations.
22 5. A public transportation trespass order issued pursuant to
23 this section may, with respect to the person against whom the
24 order is issued, do any or all of the following:
25 (a) Prohibit the person from entering onto the property of the
26 public mass transportation system for a specified period not to
27 exceed 18 months;
28 (b) Limit the access of the person to transit services offered by
29 the public mass transportation for a specified period not to exceed
30 18 months; or
31 (c) Impose any other appropriate restrictions or prohibitions
32 on the person with respect to entering the property of the public
33 mass transportation system or using the transit services offered by
34 the public mass transportation system.
35 6. A public transportation trespass order issued pursuant to
36 this section must be consistent with all other applicable federal,
37 state or local laws that protect civil rights and ensure public access
38 to a public mass transportation system.
39 7. A person who is subject to a public transportation trespass
40 order issued pursuant to this section and who violates such an
41 order is guilty of a misdemeanor.
42 8. A person against whom a public transportation trespass
43 order has been issued pursuant to this section may, at any time
44 after issuance of the order, file a petition with the court that issued
45 the order requesting modification or termination of the order.
